					<item>
				<guid>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-706753#post-4015185</guid>
				<title>(no title)</title>
				<link>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-706753/scp-1435#post-4015185</link>
				<description></description>
				<pubDate>Sat, 06 Oct 2018 00:18:23 +0000</pubDate>
				<wikidot:authorName>Gabriel McQueen</wikidot:authorName>				<wikidot:authorUserId>4558836</wikidot:authorUserId>				<content:encoded>
					<![CDATA[
						 <p>Admittedly, this is pretty nit-picky, especially on a fairly old article, but, in terms of scientific language, &quot;Testing has revealed no anomalies present in any of its composite materials&quot; bothers me, because it suggests that they have proved a negative. Phrasing such as &quot;Testing has not revealed any anomalies present in any of its composite materials&quot; gets the same point across, but leaves the ever present scientific thought open, that, &quot;just because we can't detect something, doesn't mean it's not there.&quot;</p> 
				 	]]>
				</content:encoded>							</item>
